If you can use JPQL instead of a native query you could use the following approach:

Let&#39;s imagine you have an entity Person. Then you can define a projection for the person just containing the names like this: 

    package de.models;
    
    public record PersonNames(String vorname, String nachname) {
    }

You can use JPQL`s constructor expression creating this dynamically with createQuery:

    List&lt;PersonNames&gt; p = entityManager.createQuery(
    				&quot;SELECT new de.models.PersonNames(vorname, nachname) FROM Person p&quot;,
    				PersonNames.class
    		).getResultList();

Now this is not very generic and not really for a Class T, but if you really need a generic approach you kind of have to create it yourself. A very simple implementation could be 

    public &lt;T&gt; List&lt;T&gt; findT(Class&lt;T&gt; clazz) {

		String constructorVariables = Arrays.stream(clazz.getDeclaredFields())
				.map(Field::getName)
				.reduce((s1, s2) -&gt; s1 + &quot;, &quot; + s2)
				.orElse(&quot;&quot;);

		var p = entityManager.createQuery(
				&quot;SELECT new &quot; + clazz.getName() + &quot;(&quot; + constructorVariables + &quot;) FROM Person p&quot;,
				clazz
		).getResultList();
    }

In this approach the projection-class needs to have the same field names as the database-table columns.

How you can fix it:

**Create a custom object** 

       public class PersonWithCountObjects {
    
      private String name;
    
      private int age;
    
      private int objectsCount;
    
      public PersonWithCountObjects(String name, int age, int objectsCount) {
        this.name = name;
        this.age = age;
        this.objectsCount = objectsCount;
      }
      
      //getter &amp;&amp; setter and others methods
    
      
    }


**In your PersonRepository  create a DTO projection**

A DTO projection allows you to fetch fewer columns and you wont risk any LazyInitializationException.

      @Query(&quot;SELECT new your.packages.path.to.PersonWithCountObjects &quot; +
          &quot; (person.name, person.age, count(person.objects)) &quot; +
          &quot; FROM Person person &quot;)
       List&lt;PersonWithCountObjects&gt; getPersonsWithObjectsCount();

And after it in your `methodB()` you will replace
 

    List&lt;Person&gt; personList = personRepository.findAll();
with 

    List&lt;PersonWithCountObjects&gt; personList = personRepository.getPersonsWithObjectsCount();

and make it `public` because you have `@Transactional` annotation on it

you dont need to have this line of code(`int objectSize = methodD(person)`) and also `methodD` you by default will have objects count for every person in field `objectsCount` from `PersonWithCountObjects`


And your for loop will look so:

    for (PersonWithCountObjects person : personList) {
                if (person.getObjectsCount() &lt; 50) {
