Ahhh, I wouldn&#39;t be doing this constantly, if that&#39;s what you&#39;re doing, that&#39;s very expensive.

It is likely that `updateScaledImage` is blocking the Event Dispatching Thread, preventing the UI from been painted until it completes OR your paint routine is blocking the Event Dispatching Thread during a paint pass, but that&#39;s all just guess work, as you&#39;ve not provided a runnable example.

As stated, the likely cause is somewhere in your code, identifying it, is another issue.

What I&#39;ve done in the past is used a &quot;coalescing callback&quot; coupled with a fast/low quality scaling approach.

This means, until there is a sufficient delay between resize events, I&#39;d be using a fast/low quality scaling approach to render &quot;something&quot; to the screen.  Once a &quot;sufficient delay&quot; between resize events occurs, then I&#39;d trigger a slow/high quality scale pass in a background thread, eventually updating the UI with this version.

Now remember, Swing is single threaded and NOT thread safe.  This means you shouldn&#39;t be executing blocking or long running operations within the Event Dispatching Thread and you shouldn&#39;t be updating the UI (or any state the UI relies on) from outside the Event Dispatching Thread.

To this end, I&#39;ve made us of a Swing `Timer` (to act as my &quot;coalescing callback&quot; workflow) and a `SwingWorker` to perform the high quality scale.

[![enter image description here][1]][1]

*nb: The original image is 1920x1080. I&#39;m also applying an `AlphaComposite` when the component is using the &quot;fast scaling&quot;, so you can see when the &quot;high quality&quot; image becomes available.*

